Why is ISIS able to persist?
New York – Lethal terrorist attacks in Istanbul, Dhaka, and Baghdad show that the grip of the Islamic State (ISIS) has reached Europe, North Africa, the Middle East, and Asia.
The longer ISIS remains strong in Syria and Iraq, the longer such mass slaughters will be perpetrated by its terrorist network.
But ISIS is not particularly hard to eradicate.
The problem is that the countries involved in Iraq and Syria, including the United States and its allies, have not made ISIS their primary enemy.
This should have changed.
ISIS has a small fighting force, with the US predicting between 20,000 to 25,000 fighters in Iraq and Syria, and around 5,000 in Libya.
In comparison to active military personnel in Syria (125,000), Iraq (271,500), Saudi Arabia (233,500), Turkey (510,600), and Iran (523,000), ISIS is negligible.
In September 2014, President Barack Obama pledged to "strike and ultimately defeat" ISIS, but the US and its allies, including Saudi Arabia, Turkey, and Israel (behind the scenes), focused on toppling Syrian President Bashar al-Assad.
Recently, Israeli Army Brigadier General Herzi Halevi candidly stated (as relayed to me by a journalist present at his speech): "Israel does not want to see the situation in Syria end with ISIS defeated, great powers leaving the region, and Israel facing stronger Hezbollah and Iran."
Israel opposes ISIS, but its greater concern is Iran behind Assad.
Assad allows Iran to support Israel's two main quasi-military opponents – Hezbollah and Hamas.
Therefore, Israel's focus is on toppling Assad rather than defeating ISIS.
Influenced by neoconservatism, for the United States, the war in Syria is a continuation of the global American hegemony project proposed by Defense Secretary Richard Cheney and Deputy Secretary of State Paul Wolfowitz at the end of the Cold War.
In 1991, Wolfowitz told American General Wesley Clark:
"But we did learn one thing from the Gulf War: that we could use force in the region – in the Middle East – and the Soviets would not stop us.
Before the next superpower challenges us, we have about five to ten years to clean up the old Soviet regimes – Syria, Iran (as originally stated), Iraq.
The United States' multiple wars in the Middle East – Afghanistan, Iraq, Syria, Libya, etc. – were to oust the Soviets and, later, the Russians from competition and establish American hegemony.
These "efforts" have been abysmal failures.
For Saudi Arabia and Israel, the main goal was to topple Assad to weaken Iran.
<s>Turkey is part of the massive proxy war between Shia Iran and Sunni Saudi Arabia, which is playing out on battlefields in Syria and Yemen, and along the frontlines of more intense Shia-Sunni polarization in divided countries such as Bahrain, including Saudi Arabia itself.
<s>Overthrowing Assad would strengthen Turkey's regional position.
<s>But now Turkey faces three opponents at its southern border: Assad, ISIS, and nationalist Kurds.
<s>So far, ISIS has been less important for Turkey than Assad and the Kurds.
<s>However, terrorist attacks orchestrated by ISIS could change that.
Russia and Iran also pursue their own regional interests through proxy wars and support for paramilitary operations.
But both countries have expressed willingness to cooperate with the United States in combating ISIS, and they can also cooperate on other issues.
So far, the United States has remained indifferent because its focus is on overthrowing Assad.
The US foreign policy establishment condemns Russian President Putin's support for Assad, while Russia condemns the US attempt to overthrow Assad.
These complaints appear to be at odds but are not.
Attempts by the United States and its allies to overthrow Assad violate the UN Charter, while Russia's support for Assad upholds the Charter's stipulated right of self-defense for Syria.
Of course, Assad is a tyrant, but the UN Charter does not grant any country the power to choose which tyrant to overthrow.
The enduring presence of ISIS highlights three strategic flaws in US foreign policy, as well as one fatal tactical flaw.
Firstly, neoconservatism's demand for achieving American hegemony through regime change is not only an ignorant display of bloodthirstiness; it is also a classic example of imperialism that overreaches itself.
Everywhere the United States has attempted this, it has ended in failure.
Syria and Libya are the latest examples.
Second, the CIA has funded and trained Sunni militants through secret operations in Saudi Arabia for years.
In turn, these militants gave rise to ISIS, which was a direct (perhaps unintended) consequence of the same policy pursued by the CIA and its Saudi collaborators.
Third, viewing Iran and Russia as unreconcilable enemies of the United States is largely a self-fulfilling outdated prophecy.
Realigning relations with both countries is possible.
Fourth, at the tactical level, the US attempt to fight a two-front war against Assad and ISIS has failed.
Whenever Assad is weakened, Sunni jihadists, including ISIS and the Nusra Front (al-Nusira Front), will fill the vacuum.
If the US, Russia, Saudi Arabia, and Iran provide air cover and logistical support, Assad and his Syrian allies can defeat ISIS.
Of course, Assad will continue to rule; of course, Russia will continue to be Syria’s ally; and of course, Iran will gain influence there.
Terrorist attacks will undoubtedly continue, perhaps for some time under the guise of ISIS; but the organization will be driven out of its operational bases in Syria and Iraq.
These results can not only eradicate ISIS from the Middle East; they can also lay the groundwork for more comprehensive regional de-escalation.
The US and Russia could begin to reverse the new cold war through joint efforts to expel jihadist terrorism.
(NATO's commitment not to admit Ukraine or upgrade its ballistic missile defense in Eastern Europe would also help.)
There are other benefits as well.
Tackling ISIS cooperatively could give Saudi Arabia and Turkey reasons and opportunities to find new practical arrangements with Iran.
Israel's security can be strengthened through Israel fostering cooperative economic and geo-political relations with Iran, which in turn increases the chances of a final peace agreement between Israel and Palestine.
The rise of ISIS is a sign of strategic deficiencies in the West – particularly in the United States.
The West can defeat ISIS.
The question is whether the US will undertake the strategic reassessment necessary to achieve this goal.
